abstract: On HBO, Instagram — even Fox News — aspirants are having a meta debate: How do you counterprogram a reality-TV president?
snippet: On HBO, Instagram — even Fox News — aspirants are having a meta debate: How do you counterprogram a reality-TV president?
lead_paragraph: You can’t miss the peak of Beto O’Rourke’s 2018 Texas Senate campaign in HBO’s “Running with Beto.” Maybe you’ve already seen it, on your phone or in a Facebook post: Mr. O’Rourke responding passionately to a question about N.F.L. players taking a knee to protest racism and police brutality.

headline_main: In the Democratic Primary, the Media Hits Are the Message

abstract: The competitive lanes are set as candidates vie for black voters, women, younger voters — but they are fluid. One thing seems sure: Joseph R. Biden’s lead will be tested.
snippet: The competitive lanes are set as candidates vie for black voters, women, younger voters — but they are fluid. One thing seems sure: Joseph R. Biden’s lead will be tested.
lead_paragraph: NEWTON, Iowa — Joseph R. Biden Jr. has built an early lead in the month since he entered the presidential campaign, confidently projecting himself as the Democratic front-runner and the candidate best positioned to defeat President Trump.

headline_main: With the 2020 Democratic Field Set, Candidates Begin the Races Within the Race
headline_print_headline: Democrats Begin the Race Within the 2020 Race
byline_original: By Jonathan Martin and Reid J. Epstein

abstract: Stuck in the polls and contending with a loaded Democratic field, Mr. Booker called for a deeper primary conversation during a four-day swing through Iowa.
snippet: Stuck in the polls and contending with a loaded Democratic field, Mr. Booker called for a deeper primary conversation during a four-day swing through Iowa.
lead_paragraph: BURLINGTON, Iowa — As Senator Cory Booker swept through Iowa on a four-day visit over Memorial Day weekend, he called on his often overflowing crowds to approach the presidential primary campaign through a new paradigm.

headline_main: The Insults Trump Has Hurled at 2020 Democrats
byline_original: By K.K. Rebecca Lai and Karen Yourish

abstract: Corrections appearing in print on Sunday, May 26, 2019.
snippet: Corrections appearing in print on Sunday, May 26, 2019.

abstract: The 2020 candidates who seek to oust Trump must defend liberal democracy against illiberalism at home and abroad.
snippet: The 2020 candidates who seek to oust Trump must defend liberal democracy against illiberalism at home and abroad.
lead_paragraph: Every political campaign involves a choice between elevating political discourse and degrading it. The 2016 election brought a pornographic film star into prime time and made “pussy” front-page news. How it could get any worse in 2020 is difficult to imagine. But the problem isn’t the word “pussy” and the pornification of politics, however demeaning; the problem is the word “nationalism” and the abandonment of liberalism.

headline_main: Don’t Let Nationalists Speak for the Nation
headline_print_headline: Don’t Let Nationalists Speak for the Nation

abstract: An inflexible agenda and a global retreat.
snippet: An inflexible agenda and a global retreat.
lead_paragraph: In Australia a week ago, the party of the left lost an election it was supposed to win, to a conservative government headed by an evangelical Christian who won working-class votes by opposing liberal climate policies. In India last week, the Hindu-nationalist prime minister, Narendra Modi, won an overwhelming electoral victory. And as of this writing, Europeans are electing a Parliament that promises to have more populist representation than before.

abstract: The Washington governor has long been a leading voice on climate change. He believes he will gain prominence as more voters learn of his record and proposals.
snippet: The Washington governor has long been a leading voice on climate change. He believes he will gain prominence as more voters learn of his record and proposals.
lead_paragraph: RAYMOND, N.H. — For years, climate change was an issue of passionate concern to a few voters, but never enough to ripple presidential politics. The Hillary Clinton-Donald Trump debates in 2016 notoriously did not include any questions from moderators about global warming.
